reviewText:
i agree with the reviewer that said at moments, it got a little bit cheesy, but 99% of the movie was cute, fun and the ending message of course was really great.

jennifer garner just glowed in this role. i love alias, but it was nice to see her smile and laugh in this role :)

i definitely recommend this :) &hearts;

This is the type of movie that will generally leave some smiling and glad that movies like this can still succeed in Hollywood, while others will cringe as it may represent fluff at its worst. I fell somewhere in the middle of these extremes.

THE GOOD:

1) Jennifer Garner just lights up the screen no matter what she's doing or whatever the script asks of her;

2) Mark Ruffalo, who is always outstanding in more serious fare ("You Can Count On Me"), displays an unusual degree of charm and approachability that most of today's leading men could not conjure up;

3) The premise, while not original, is fun and starts off very well;

4) The director creates a wonderful palette of color that works very well in both time-frames;

5) Many scenes are given a much needed lift via great songs from the 1980s;

6) The movie actually surprised me a couple of times and for once one of the heroines "rivals" is not an easy to hate witch; and

7) The ending, which I won't give away, made me smile and that is not a bad thing at all.

THE NOT SO GOOD/AWFUL:

1) The script is simple a mess. It has no structure nor explanations as to why the leading character turned out to be the ubber witch that she allegedly turned out to be;

2) The whole magazine "redesign" plot development and associated plot links simply does not cut it as they are poorly executed and simply make no sense;

3) While Jennifer Garner works her magic with the slim pickings that she gets, but the movie spends way too little time getting into how a 13 year-old would feel if she woke up and was 30 years old. There is so much potential comic relief and the character would have been more grounded if the writer had spent any time trying to go beyond what essentially becomes a very badly written movie about corporate America;

4) The DVD has a series of deleted scenes that may have helped to shape the movie better as it has the feel of a cut and paste that it tries to hide with songs from the 1980s.

From the above you may get the impression that I really disliked this movie, but that is not the case. Jennifer Garner's presence and my desire to see something frothy made this the perfect rental. I cannot give it a strong recommendation because it's a mess, but it has cute moments and sometimes gets it right. I just wish that they have nixed the impossible to stomach whole magazine redesign fiasco and focused on executing the movies title.
